\details{
\strong{What this is for -- and what it is not.} \code{cier_simulate()} exists for
(a) power analysis and study design, (b) method comparison on \emph{planted}
patterns, (c) recovery and property tests, and (d) replicating published
simulation designs. It is \strong{not} evidence of real-world validity:
simulated carelessness is more stylized than even instructed carelessness,
and Schroeders et al. (2022) found that a detector's simulation-trained
advantage did not transfer to real data. Anchor every real-world accuracy
claim to labeled real data instead.

\strong{Attentive model.} A graded response model in the factor-analytic
parameterization: one factor per scale in \code{items}, default loadings 0.7,
identity factor correlations, latent traits from \code{trait_distribution}.
Reverse-keyed items load negatively, so the returned matrix is \strong{raw}
(as-clicked) -- keying-sensitive indices reverse-score internally from
\code{items}, exactly as with field data. Item thresholds come from \code{marginals}
(named presets or explicit per-item / per-scale probability vectors;
default \code{"peaked"}, a symmetric triangular distribution) or from raw
\code{thresholds}; the two are mutually exclusive.

\strong{Patterns.} \code{patterns} weights the eight recognized styles: \code{random},
\code{straightline} (anchor / switch knobs), \code{midpoint}, \code{extreme}, \code{diagonal}
(with a bounce option), \code{alternating}, \code{markov}, and \code{speeder} (attentive
\emph{content} but careless \emph{times} -- content indices should miss it, timing
should catch it). The default weights every style equally, following the
equal-allocation design of Welz & Alfons (2023); no published study
estimates a real-world style mixture, so the default makes no prevalence
claim. Per-style knobs go in \code{pattern_params} (e.g.
\code{list(straightline = list(anchor = "value", value = 5))}) and are recorded
verbatim in \code{truth$params} -- the truth always documents exactly what was
applied.

\strong{Extent and onset.} Each careless row independently draws an extent:
\code{full} (the whole row), \code{partial} (careless from a sampled onset to the
end), or \code{temporary} (careless on a bounded window, then recovered). The
careless span is the \strong{inclusive} column range \verb{[onset_item, offset_item]}: full is \verb{[1, p]}; partial samples its onset from
\code{onset_window} (default \code{round(c(0.3, 0.8) * p)}, the sampled-onset design
of Welz & Alfons 2023) and runs to \code{p}; temporary additionally samples an
offset of at most \code{p - 1}, so a recovery tail of at least one item always
follows (its onset is sampled below the window's upper bound where needed,
and the window may be as short as one item). \code{temporary} therefore needs
at least three items. Both the content overwrite and the careless time
shift are confined to that span.

\strong{Response times.} Lognormal per-item times with a per-respondent pace
intercept (\code{respondent_sd}), so the attentive and careless distributions
overlap -- by design, nothing separates perfectly. Careless rows shift to
the careless log-mean \emph{inside their span only}. The defaults (attentive
median 8 s/item; careless median 1.5 s/item, below the 2 s/item per-page
screening floor of Bowling et al. 2023; \code{sigma = 0.5};
\code{respondent_sd = 1.2}) are \strong{documented conventions anchored to cited
thresholds, not estimates}, calibrated so the planted speeding is
detectable by \code{\link[=cier_page_time]{cier_page_time()}}'s default rule while the total-time
rank-AUC stays inside the .66-.92 range reported across real datasets
(Goldammer et al. 2024; Huang et al. 2012). Every parameter is overridable
through \code{timing}. The truth's \code{speeded} column records which rows carry
careless times; in this version that is every careless row, including
speeders.

\strong{Attention checks.} With \code{n_checks > 0}, separate five-point
instructed-response checks are generated (never written into
\verb{$responses}): careless rows fail each check with \code{p_fail_careless},
attentive rows with \code{p_fail_attentive}. The defaults 0.75 / 0.05 are
documented conventions -- no published point estimates exist; the
bracketing evidence is Goldammer et al.'s (2024) bogus-item AUCs of
.66-.76 and Bruhlmann et al.'s (2020) 92 bogus-item failures among 394
respondents. Failure is probabilistic on both sides, so direct checks
never separate the groups perfectly either.

\strong{Reproducibility.} With \code{seed}, the generator runs on a local RNG state
(the session stream is saved and restored), and the same seed reproduces
the returned object bytewise.
}
